A Republican Strategy to Oppose Obama's Re-Election
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, affirming that electoral fraud in the United States is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning.
The Republicans’ lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for holding elections in each state.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of U.S. governments have announced new laws that complicate the procedure for registration or the passage of ballots.
This phenomenon has gained momentum following the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court document exists.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state had asked voters to show a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana Act.
The Republican authorities hurried to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states forcing voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new voters do not have such an identity card in 2012.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often to be paid to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years old do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are considered voters who vote more for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who are more likely to vote for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic votes.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in 2011 in eight states promoted laws that abolished the registration of voters on Election Day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns for voter registration in the 2004 general elections have helped to register about 10 million citizens.
As a result of the measures adopted since 2009, the share of registration of new voters in 2010 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they make up only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites representing 76% of voters accounted for only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of the democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the display of a photo ID card.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics criticize the partisan nature of the passed laws and see it as a clear goal to influence the results in the states that will determine 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Prostate cancer early detection: should the test be done or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes shows erroneous results, with false negative or false positive results that lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This leads to greater reluctance of the already undecided men to perform early detection tests.
Should the test be done or not?
We have received the opinion of two experts.
In the studies conducted in the US, there were numerous inter-control factors, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in the mortality of patients with and without early detection.
This study also showed that in a follow-up observation after 12 years, the probability of metastasis formation is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection was performed.
Therefore, I recommend the test from the age of 50 years or 40 years, respectively, if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also at higher risk.
The most important thing is to make the right decision as soon as a cancer is detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient needs to really understand the extent of the risk of his cancer by showing him the possible options in which prostate cancer can remain untreated if it does not impair the quality of life in the long term, and in these cases, it is more likely to opt for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer do not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to their lives.
They are suggested to be actively monitored and offered treatment when the disease progresses.
Increasingly, the criteria for deciding who should be treated and who should not are determined.
That is why I recommend the test to be carried out.
However, the most important thing is to talk to your doctor to determine if it should be done or not.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has developed an instrument that makes it possible to assess the pros and cons of the PSA test.
