The Higgs Boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has sparked some excitement last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but empirically not yet observed.
But for the physicists, it is not yet completely certain that this is really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still lacking to be completely sure.
Still, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of cheating, and let’s take a look at what it’s about.
There is an indispensable law in this world, which means that two objects cannot be present in the same place at the same time.
It’s not possible to break this rule – and don’t try it too hard as you’ll get hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that they also have such a law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, when they are in the same "quantum state", with this "state" consisting of some of their properties in general.
On the basis of this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and kindly obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons move, an evil band of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure by the Berkeley Laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing) these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bot" of the electromagnetic force.
If a particle accelerates with an electrical charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disrupted" exactly at this point, into something like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stabilized field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, needs to be "disrupted" in order for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen has to reach very high energies, a bit comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be shredded by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator like CERN is needed - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself on the refrigerator.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon by the way) do not have a mass.
For what can all this research be “good” now, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to study all the deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who most eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major flaws, as it does not provide an explanation for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Implications
The impact of these studies on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there were none.
By the way: in the early 60s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle – who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first permanent laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 – has already told us that the laser was initially considered a “laboratory toy”.
Imagine yourself...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras around the world and earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you can never really know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its committee on "Death in Dignity", Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate needs to resume soon, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important subject area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that ate him had left him a two-year period.
"They gave me five years to live, I've made seven years," he said halfheartedly, lying in his bed at the palliative care home of Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he resignedly agrees to be helped with the meal.
Bravely, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to be cured of my diarrhea, as this is humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this ailment.
“Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is pinking while standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards," he notes.
Because according to several people who work in palliative care, large events take place amid these setbacks.
The patients who are referred to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer crowded with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who take care of them.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and by drowning.”
But through the illness, I really got to know my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I have no more desires in life,” she says, before accepting that she is put on a mask that helps her breathe.
In the coming days, she still expects a final visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
At the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers offers body care and food intake assistance.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, a bed for palliative care is provided for 11,700 people.
That is very little, considering that one day we will all die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or pepsi, as desired.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help family members and patients alike,” says Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, there is no day like the other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family reunion in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows while being insulted in his honor, a 36-year-old young man, surrounded by his parents, his wife, and his two young children, tragically dies after trying everything he can to...
“For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when they have reached the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal area, more or less specialize exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
Precisely this large inadequacy in Quebec’s health care ensures that several physicians specializing in palliative care face the adoption of a law to regulate euthanasia and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care personalities such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before being accepted to go to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without taking any action to relieve her.
I fear that patients want to die just because they don’t receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients despite the worst prognosis until the last day.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued a troubled chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I would stop treatment, she replied that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have been asked to die thank the caregivers for not fulfilling this wish after their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Montreal-based Society of Home Palliative Care, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in the patient falling asleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
