A Constitution with the Breaking Rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever regarding the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given this plenary two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional, amended text for almost two years now, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his “autocratic delirium” by continuing to “break his word” and “trample the law with his feet.”
On the side of its proponents, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
It is also a way for the president to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
According to confirmations in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to an overhauled vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals did not respond to the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt that they had not been able to put their views into practice.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
To reach the decision-making capacity, 11 persons, including deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly unanimously adopted.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time for prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum of the Constituent Assembly was not going exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had hoped to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is evidence of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who see this only as a propaganda blow, are responding with “pretty sanctity.”
According to them, the islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They have particular regard to Article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "the persons who are asked for a statement have not been elected and do not possess any democratic legitimacy.
You can see in this the first signs of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is far less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious commitment to be recognized.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been partly trained in the French system," reassured Alexis Blouet, who is writing a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He concedes, however, that "there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
In particular, reference is made here to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on it."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticized for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will there be a ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights groups have demanded.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text, which they regard as a threat to freedom.
The reality of blasphemy is being maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, the article no longer refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of salt
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons to visit Israel.
Bend before the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on the water, silencing the storm of the sea and fishing.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the temples are located in Jerusalem.
Believers here commit the path of suffering or the cross path of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the church of the tomb on Mount Golgotha, where the place of crucifixion, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Walls of Lamentation, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take a trip to the top
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies, which Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rocky wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain, there is a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the mountain top.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is once the Israel Museum near the Knesset (parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea, found in rock caves in the Judean desert, as well as approximately 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits, are kept.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
It houses the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most striking section is the memorial for the children, which was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room, there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the lands in which they died are uttered.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air heats up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathing all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and therefore carries even non-swimmers without problems on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sols) and healing sludge, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of stressed nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
These are the secrets of the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city passed the famous sea route, which connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which he led a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow alleys named after signs of constellation.
Fortune is supposed to be the legend after all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed today.
List of attractions for tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is preferred not in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you can usually get there by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a expressway and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stations that connects the sub-city with the upper city.
Precisely speaking, it is an underground cable car.
A ride within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including transfers for a ride of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is at rest.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales, and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with ham and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-fed cats that roam the streets comfortably and unhindered.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of cars parked.
The cats like lively places and do not say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, which is an increase of 51% compared to the comparison period in 2010, before the visa waiver on February 9, 2011.
'The Great and Powerful' Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While lawmakers and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families who remained in the home.
On December 1, a law came into force that requires every migrant to pass a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in retail trade.
However, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future, according to the Federal Migration Agency.
In doing so, one must not only take language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language proficiency must be demonstrated for both obtaining and renewing the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, Problems and Protection of Rights
The totality of the examination posts will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the press several times before the law came into force: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the requirement of having to demonstrate language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, according to the spokespersons of the Migration Authority, the aim is to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of working migrants," said Viktor Sebelev, the head of the representative of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical examination encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who will put him in a dark, narrow barracks under the pretext of help, where he will endure dozens of his own months without food and documents and will spend 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have received many complaints from our migrants.
"In the homeland you are promised one, and upon arrival you will be cheated, get their passports taken away and will not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the main administration for labour migration of the Tajik migration authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they are not only unable to speak the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, as rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable basic education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
“It’s difficult without language skills,” they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, then there is no examination and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers remain illegal in Russia.
"Welcome" or "No entry for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly forged and we are not registered, and then cases of blackmail arise.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
“Don’t worry about the cost of the wrong papers.”
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be forged.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Agency.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for free: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests in this way paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
That’s more than double the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the main immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased, is agreed by both officials and civil rights activists.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who pass the test for the first time that they will get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered positions in areas where there is no need for active understanding with people.
Interior Ministry Ignores Illegal Arms Market
Proportion of legal weapons in criminal offences extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior plans to tighten the gun law for private gun owners.
In this way, the authorities react to the recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven deaths during the amok run of the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Winogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairperson of the Duma Security and Anti-Corruption Committee, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose author - representatives of various arms associations - urged the authorities to refrain from "meaningless aggravations".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal justice , Wassily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while for the same period a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, you can find any weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from the factories to the officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by both Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,” Baranez said.
On the second channel come illegal weapons, the guards are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons that were stolen both from the police weapons chambers and directly from law enforcement officials.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military stockpiles.
In many military camps there were frequent explosions.
“There is evidence that in some cases it was a fire foundation to cover up the lack of weapons,” the former military official said.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private armaments factories that are not able to withstand international competition and therefore throw weapons at hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a production of its own, sometimes handicrafts, and a mafia that organizes the smuggling,” the former military official explains.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on weapons.
According to investigators, the bulk of illegal weapons come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market were there because of the “indebtedness of those responsible who have been dealing with weapons in their work,” the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% come from theft in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun shop who doesn’t want to be named assures that weapons found in illegal excavations haven’t been bought for a long time because they are obsolete.
According to him, it is more common for dealers to obtain the replenishment in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, such as a TT type pistol, is purchased via a flag carrier.
The weapon is displayed and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
“Of course, the police are aware of everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the plan to detect crimes, periodically carry out check purchases from dealers offering illegal weapons,” the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
