Birth in space
Earth in Danger.
Earth warming or collision with a killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth inhabitants on board set out in search of a replacement planet.
To save humanity, the important question is how can we reproduce in gravitylessness or on the replacement planet?
In my opinion, there are not many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
“It’s Mars and Venus,” says Vladimir Surdin, a scientist at the Sternberg Institute.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at great heights or in the orbit of Venus, that is, in space.
The question of reproduction in space was initially addressed by the researchers with regard to the flora.
Already half a century ago, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of the peas grown in orbit did not differ in the slightest from the earthly species.
It was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how gravitylessness affects the development of embryos.
It develops a very normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to stop; it has to be able to stand on its feet and start moving," explains Vladimir Sychev, head of the Institute for Medical and Biological Problems at RAN.
Without a solid ground, the chicks swarm wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely waned.
The chicks did not respond to light and noise.
Four days later, they simply died.
“Two times we let chicks sneak in and then shut it down because it’s simply impossible to work with them there,” Vladimir Sychev says of the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized and sent into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats got young.
The problem of reproduction directly in space could not be solved so far.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans could do this in principle.
The Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
From ethical considerations, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was with Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagulls flew away from it, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Can it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered that question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child’s father, Andrijan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Swetlana Sawizkaja, who was twice in orbit and even worked outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there remains a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, who after long flights everything went well and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even when flying into orbit," concludes Cosmonaut Waleri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet humanity must seek new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the generation of artificial gravity.
The hydrolab in the Cosmonauts Preparatory Center is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for work in open space.
The water represents the weightlessness.
Although adults feel water as pleasant, it is a foreign environment; however, infants feel water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders bear witness to the fact that life on land originated in the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the womb of the mother for about 9 months in amniotic fluid, and the fact that it can then more easily get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swim only 2 weeks pass.
“That’s too little time to forget something,” says baby swimmer Marina Aksenova.
While for a newborn child, therefore, weightlessness is a much more natural state, the woman does not come out without gravity.
In a state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles form enormously quickly and thus also decreases the ability to squeeze the child out.
All right, let's get around this by birth-initiating aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Waleri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the grounding, the organism cannot train the skeleton and the muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a stress suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply miss what is essential to his life.
"This experiment, which we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely unfit person," says Igor Pestov, head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical Biological Problems of the RAN.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it will become a reality when the inhabitants of Earth in their spaceships break up into a distant planet, which will be the home for their offspring born in space.
