Is it because the inspectors are better?
I certainly don’t, but as I said, I don’t like comparisons like that.
It should also be noted that those countries that are an example for us are also struggling with problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have anything to do with our authority, would they?
As far as the Czech legislation is concerned, what was the significance for your authority of the amendment of the Procurement Act, do you already feel any impact?
Given the fact that this novelle is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an impact on our exams.
Since our checks take place afterward, we have to expect a certain delay here.
So far, we are more likely to feel the effects in the preparatory phase of future checks - so we have introduced the new control instrument "Detecting risks of ineconomy" and examined and analysed with this almost 14,000 public contracts - here the changes will of course have an effect, as the thresholds have changed, the conditions have been changed for certain types of checks.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positively, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be observed.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to an audit are liable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the extent that any non-compliance with the law on the award of contracts amounts to a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense, then, to make the law even stricter?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a form error that does not affect the actual decision-making.
Such a system only puts even greater pressure on the bureaucracy.
Where's the way out of here?
First of all, let’s say which path is not targeted.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not lighten the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now banned or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the chairman of the government cannot simply come and hinder the control office, whose duty is now to control compliance with the law, in its activity.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we do as if nothing were.
The Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain operations - and this is also true for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely due to form errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think we are missing.
