Your foreign plans are not exactly small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you handle these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be carried in the luggage compartment. And of course we have to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, so far it has always worked without problems, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travels abroad you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, where everything works better than ours, we were just in Russia witnessing that in the East everything is still in its beginnings.
In front of Prague, Moscow is absolutely not suitable for people with disabilities. There, it is still unusual when someone is travelling alone in a wheelchair in the city center.
It is not even natural to leave a wheelchair driver in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what respect do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we hang out with...
However, it should be noted that the improvement of the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in the public and freedom of access is a thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come out of our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a caregiver at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in getting involved with something intense.
