There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is part of it.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live a full life and develop if they have the means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, this is not only progress for themselves, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise on many things and also demand some discipline.
This, however, is, in my opinion, perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and if they then find that they have to rehearse twice a week, have to complete preparation phases and spend a lot of time on concert trips, then the enthusiasm of many quickly disappears.
But this is how it works everywhere, in any band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
