Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the member countries of the European Space Agency, making it the second member of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Of course, Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, so they did not always encounter understanding.
I recall here, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP deer, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals, he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's world-recognized contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the earth's side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to brake the Draisine.
The information in this regard comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-propelled rifles.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents handed down, it is evident that the research was advanced to the stage of practical tests.
The research was interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket originated by Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the specialist press, and the following year, the work "Rakieta - torpeda vojettrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish an aerospace company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be expected that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Society PTA tried to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact, the PTA became a regular member as early as the fall of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the deputy chairman of the International Space Federation.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 began flight tests in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w desert with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for observation of high-altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was halted.
The successor of the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a capacity of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a capacity of 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight height for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth noting that Poland joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek.
Repealing the Nonprofit Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court lifted the Non-Profit Works Act.
This decision sparked a lively discussion in the public.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
Liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in a permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of labour (wage), there are price tensions.
By this term is meant a state in which the manufacturer tries to exist by importing favourable goods into economic competition by "undercutting" competition in order to rip off a larger market share and increase its profit.
On a large scale, this means for most companies moving their production abroad or purchasing cheaply there, or giving up their business, resulting in high unemployment in countries with comparable high labour costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment caused by it, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is further exacerbated by the fact that gentlemen entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage they have caused to society as a whole.
This situation is generally known, so concrete statistics are superfluous at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates a situation in the individual economies in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words: Governments hand over their own populations to private capital regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in amendments to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the own population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is due, on the one hand, to economic compulsion in the case of long-term unemployment, and, on the other, to the reduction of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as ever-increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
For several years now, there have been public food dispensers in Germany for the poor who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regular cases where employees receive such a low wage that the state has to increase their income to the minimum.
Such a scandal was also uncovered in the case of auxiliary personnel employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all the southern EU states will undoubtedly result in the same state in which people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in their social level (as was the case in the 19th century), or to work for a hunger wage on the fringes of society, hoping to invest in land.
This naturally raises the question of where this capital comes from.
When it comes from another EU country, poverty only migrates from one country to another; or capital remains the same, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or in Africa, the workers work at all for a fraction of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim to the extreme that the state is not allowed to participate in its own economy with capital, and that a planned economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital insists narrowly on its position that the state is not allowed to intervene in the economy.
But then one has to wonder whether private capital does not influence politics and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense, or even directs it.
Here is the clear answer: yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a practically omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual advantage, legislation in which virtually everything is punishable, but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that a state ministry, due to a lack of finances, commissions private law firms closely intertwined with industry with the preparation of bills.
These bills will then be passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then proceeds no longer from the people, as Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Obviously, the liberal democracies are currently quickly getting into a situation, as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic at the time of Caesar and Pompey's: "The state had long been in disarray, and the offices were occupied by force.
Against smear money, through illegal leaching of benefits or with stone and sword.
Corruption grew uninhibited, and the people went to the election with already bought votes" ... "People with character did not apply for office, so that the state did not have a consul for eight months as a result of this decline" ... "One really began to talk about that the only man in this serious situation was the one who was strong enough to be a sole proprietor of the people" ...
As it turns out, today’s society, as in antiquity, is based on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital, by its very nature, is not able to recognize and enforce the benefit for the whole of society.
The result, today as at the time, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who are not at all striving for deeper reforms.
We must therefore look for the cause of the rise of fascism and communism in the ruthless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today's standpoint, the downfall of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already taking place.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that today’s elites are completely unaware of the possible future loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, of the humanitarian and social disasters we are already witnessing today, as well as of the crimes against humanity as we know them from older and newer history.
The repeal of the Non-Profit Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political and social reforms that increase the state’s participation in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
