The movie Argo: When it's worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist protesters occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the Revolution, who had held the patronage over his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - she could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of her allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt at hostage-taking only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages at home provoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to disguise their true identity – they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film crew who allegedly visited locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in trade journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film vary - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly spiked as a result.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the floor of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable start to his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after Crime No Children's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film that does not play in the director's hometown Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that made the previous films of this director stand out from the standard of Hollywood.
Affleck, however, also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the entrance sequence of the message's storm is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story goes somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck and his team even in fictional scenes (the wrong film staff at a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many scenes in the cinematic sense.
However, with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes re-imagining reality - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the looming crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem a bit artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood co-workers, but their characters would have deserved more space, and thus they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses a bit of traction as a result, it is a film that you can follow with some interest, while enjoying the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70s.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day, and as a proof of the extent to which the ideas of the omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services are overlaid, it is sufficient.
