The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in the head - the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built bookshelf - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a nearby big company, says, "Well, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have Internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to one of these old-style libraries voluntarily, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy city in need of a visit at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to replicate the seven fictional bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as beautifully brushed concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to become master of statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architecture office MVRDV, master of bold beam diagrams and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual calmness and appeared for the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin in his face.
And while the jury was still staring around and groaning with his armpits, the rude Maas piled his exquisitely sized companion into a pyramid and ended his actionistly backed-up speech with the words: "Dear town community!"
So this is it, my proposal for the bookshelf of Spijkenisse, for the so-called bookshelf!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro expensive mountain is poured out.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjoining residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project has also been nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small-town retort, which until now had no more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incomprehensible ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory, to make a piece of contemporary architecture richer.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: Book Eldorado under cheese bells.
There is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the real pleasures of space and reading open up when climbing the topography on foot.
The glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights speak unmistakably the language of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Normally, the bookshelf stands along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We have put the classic room configuration on the head and pushed the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the center are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and home technology center.
A special joy are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall coverings, sometimes armor, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, haptics and smells are foreign.
Even incorporated architects and civil engineers shake their heads about the unknown building material.
“We wanted to work here with recycling materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm one day.
For many years, a millimetre-thin plastic fleece has been used as a base in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin fabric lasts one, two seasons, after which it is ready for the blocking waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed to four centimeters thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like a sports shoe.
After 105 steps, you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-metre-long hike, you will be rewarded in the Literaturcafé not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide for atmosphere, but above all for the right humidity in the mountains of literature.
Donations for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Bucherberg is under a glass fall, the sun even on sunny days only briefly shines inwards.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand transversely to the glass facade, serve as shade and capture much of the sunlight.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic rolls.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already dared to enter the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even refers to the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
For the first time, the optical gaps in the library – currently 70,000 – are to be filled.
The concept has come up.
The shelves are filled to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
In this way, MVRDV has succeeded in achieving that royal discipline, which is called the Foundation of Identity in the specialist jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
