As in previous constitutions, the draft states that jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
But what do you mean by “principles”?
This was and is a matter of interpretation, and it is feared that the Islamists will use the spongy formulation and the associated legal space for a stricter interpretation of Sharia.
This suggests at least one newly added article: In all matters concerning Sharia, Al-Ashar University, the country’s most important Islamic institution with great radiance in all Sunni Islam, must be taken care of.
That doesn’t have to, but it can mean that the clergy oversees legislation, which would de facto have the effect of discouraging the judiciary.
Much in the draft draft is a matter of interpretation
Also problematic: the civil military jurisdiction should continue to be maintained.
These courts served during Mubarak's reign to suppress oppositionists.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were held in military custody.
The state should also, the draft states, "protect the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote their morals and values".
This is so vaguely formulated in law that with the help of this article, state institutions could even control the content of film art and literature.
Clearly, this means nothing more than censorship.
By the way, no article explicitly defines the equality of men and women.
To do this, another forbids insulting or slandering the Prophet Muhammad and his messengers.
But what is an insult and how it should be punished remains unclear.
Equally doubtful is the wording that "insulting people" is prohibited.
Is a cartoon of the president enough or a joke at the expense of a lawyer?
A matter of interpretation, as so much in the draft, which Morsi is present for signature and will be presented "very soon" to the Egyptians for a referendum, according to his words.
"The Revolution is Back"
The opposition has been forming for weeks against the supremacy of the Islamists.
Tens of thousands gathered in unusual harmony on Friday night in Cairo’s Tahrir Square and vowed to bring the charter down before it could even take effect.
“The revolution is back and we will win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, third in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El-Baradei said the draft constitution belonged "on the garbage hill of history".
Via Twitter, he accused Morsi’s supporters of wanting to lead a “putsch against democracy.”
"If he calls the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," opposition leader Jasser Said said.
“We are not yet tired, the blood of our brothers is not yet atoned,” the Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali as saying.
And several judges announced that they did not want to monitor the referendum, which would render it invalid.
"The Qur'an is our Constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, for its part, blew to the counter-demonstration, but for the sake of caution not in Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other Nile in front of Cairo University.
Many veiled women and followers of the Salafists took part in it, shouting, "The people demand the application of God's law."
They demanded of Morsi, “Clean the land!” and affirmed, “The Qur’an is our constitution.”
A struggle for sovereignty over the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would probably have evoked civil war-like conditions.
Obviously, Morsi’s followers did not want to risk that.
The Muslim brothers stated that both the opponents of the draft constitution and the proponents had spoken out loud and clearly.
Now is the time to let the people at the ballot box decide in which direction the country should go.
A majority for the Islamist draft is considered safe.
"The word human rights does not even occur"
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry about this forced constitutional process, which was supposed to run until February and involve all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EHRO) defended the Muslim brothers while they were in prison or in court under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution," he laments in conversation with the "World on Sunday."
Morsi's expansion of power to all three powers in the state allowed the lawyer to resign.
These measures are blatant violations of democratic rules of the game and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president is de facto putting it out of action," Saeda lamented.
But without civil society organizations, a democracy cannot work.
Saeda feels left alone, also by the international community, which views the ideological struggle on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could avenge.
A protester on the Tahrir warns: "You are feeding a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfish from Norway: Is this the most stinky fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest living standards - not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country’s secret of success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty stinky fish?
You take a selection of overripe cheeses.
You place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, damp sportswear.
And load them there for a week.
One has to imagine the nose-popping smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There’s snow here, spectacular landscapes – and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn’t want to disappear.
Rakfisk is salt-soaked trout, which – depending on how stinky you would like your fish – is fermented in water for up to a year.
When in Norway the darkness comes over the country and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, well, really very specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works in the local fire department, but also organizes the festival as the so-called "Rakfisk General".
Around us, people eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
"Many people like the aquavit more than the rakfish," says Havard.
Spirits can suppress the smell.
I'll cost you a few bucks.
If you avoid getting the rakfish close to your nose, it’s not bad – like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a very different, far poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling options yet and fish was soaked in airtight saltwater tanks in the autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was then taken out after long fermentation and - undoubtedly with the help of alcohol dampened senses - consumed.
A generation ago, thousands of Norwegians looking for work were forced to leave their country and migrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and comprehensive health care.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, who not too long ago was far richer than Norway, immigrants flow.
Rakfisk is regarded as something important – as an essential, albeit strictly fragrant, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the more expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proud 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t often get into the world press, and most people don’t seem to bother with that.
Here it is still hated to call Anders Breivik by name - that racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it refers only to the "July 22 incident".
Norwegians find it hard to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Since the early 1970s, the growth of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world has been responsible for Norway’s wealth.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays of ripe rakfish and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blond hair and piercing blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Your English is just like that of most people here.
We're not very bragging, we don't like bragging.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very carefully - a large part of the industry's revenue is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the global economic crisis, everyone threw around with money that they did not even possess, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
“As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we are happy,” says Anna.
"And of course eat rakfish," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow and stand for another dish - I've had enough of Rakfisk.
Such an elf burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat sniffs me.
But in the evening, the stinkfish is back on the menu.
The hotel I stay at is one of several venues that organize a Rakfish dinner where guests can vote for the best – or perhaps the most challenging – fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-dressed showmaster surrounded by plates of rakfish.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard".
You smile and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But maybe it's the rigor of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces tough start
As Mexico’s future president Enrique Pena Nieto prepares for his inauguration, Will Grant from the BBC analyses the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, the traffic in Mexico City is very bad.
Even on better days, this is an ever-clogging city, but on Monday, a steel ring was erected, blocking several important traffic routes to the capital and causing chaos on the streets.
The aim, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidency and take over the leadership of the nation.
He faces a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has been able to prove itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 people the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy with which we can achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as the governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, expansive part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions are divided about the new head of state.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which represent a great improvement over the fragile, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with his name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect him to make real and lasting changes," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who serves as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, which works for PRI.
In particular, when it comes to security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so urgently needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace in Los Pinos, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was turned on to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
The bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left alone in the past two years at a site in Brachland near a large landfill.
During the tenure of Governor Pena Nieto, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics of Pena Nietos believe that he did not adequately address the problem of female murder during his term.
But in the worst case scenario, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the downgraded neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes that she was murdered by her life partner.
"When I arrived at her house, it seemed as if her body had been washed," Senora Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the body stiffness had already been applied.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down from the wall and is attached next to a cross that bears a single word: justice.
But this, the family says, has been denied to her so far.
The authorities treated me as if I were a chatterer, a troublemaker, a nurse.
They want their judgment to be simply accepted and their mouths shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and omissions,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the Presidential Bond on Saturday, he also takes on a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have suffered from violent crimes in the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his term.
"I hope that as president he is what he was as governor," says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Prosecution Claims: Bradley Manning Didn't Complain About Abuse
The prosecutor's office denies Bradley Manning's allegations that he was abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a rejection of the indictment due to harsh conditions of detention
The liberated U.S. Army is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The U.S. Attorney’s Office on Friday tried to establish that Army liberated Bradley Manning — accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history — missed several opportunities to complain about the alleged abuse he suffered in military custody.
At a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning’s nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not show any complaints about his treatment.
The day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to reject the indictment — Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh prison term — Manning had stated that he had considered suicide in prison.
The US military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out with Manning after their meetings with him during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been incarcerated under enhanced conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as "very professional".
The forms, so fine, contained no complaints about abuse, although Manning’s officials had questioned him directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally, and the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but they were not recorded.
“They wrote (after discussing the concerns) ‘No problems,’ and that didn’t necessarily mean I didn’t say anything at all,” Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during this meeting had been to lower his observation status to “prevention of injuries.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is one stage under the threat of suicide - to his own and the protection of others.
“I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the observational injury prevention status... in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning announced his arrest and relocation to Kuwait on Thursday, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base Prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and was once unconscious due to the heat.
Not being able to know what was happening to him or to the outside world was a burden.
“My world was shrinking on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
When he moved to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell—at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours—and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion, because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lay down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and the guards could no longer see his face, they woke him up so that he could turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned about an allegation he had made in his statement on Thursday – such as sleeping naked in his cell in Quantico one night and having to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had stated that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his ceiling during this count.
During Friday's questioning, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had stated that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before and had previously tried to show an official that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the collar of his underpants or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experience and drastically reduce his detention, should he be convicted in his trial before the military court, which is set for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offences, while other charges that are deemed to be too extreme are to be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecutor's office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning was detained in accordance with the regulations that apply to all of Quantico’s highest security guards.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, illegally publishing classified information on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing public property or documents.
If he is found guilty in all charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
Many people have been forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame emigrants – they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when insanity widened in me.
Signs referred to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Foreigners" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, not sure which one to go to.
I grew up in Central California and was called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Irene" or my friends in New York "Italian".
Later, I decided to go for "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's home, there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and my American accent won’t let me go either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when the future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to stay in Mexico instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc following the example of the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico’s war against the drug cartels, even though he did not mention details about it.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s leadership to hand over more than half of its territory to them under restraint.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
As soon as a U.S. government official makes even the slightest criticism of Mexico, one hears - in the Mexican press and among the elites of the country - complaints about how the Americans are pressing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma go on the path of war.
And yet, Mexico’s biggest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person – perhaps a parent or grandparent – was not offered a chance in Mexico and emigrated north.
And in most cases this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty goes to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may now be living the American dream, attending good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we are living — not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In your opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they wouldn’t have left.
And then we wouldn't see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that tensions exist between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are — and Mexican Americans take it badly.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel like they don’t belong to either country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but you are not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational civics want to resume their connections to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Oh, well.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge against the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
- Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to stifle such hope in the germ.
In the midst of the usual culprits, countless buildings have been laid in rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed – and for the first time rockets from Gaza have been struck near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem to be trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not – Palestinians and Israelis have become part of these turmoils.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly pat situation could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems to be anything but appropriate given the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened the hardliners on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, despite the fact that its own group had to suffer heavy losses.
Although several Hamas leaders have been killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are being suffocated in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders may conclude that they have the time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a revitalizing regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken over the Hamas party – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Cheerful Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, over Syria, where rebels could face an increasingly Islamist imprint on Bashar Assad’s overthrow, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt – by far the most populous and important Arab country – on the southern flank of Israel has changed the balance of the region in a lasting way.
Hosni Mubarak, the secularist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the fraternity with Hamas is weakened and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor who cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, have drawn an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has been able to prove itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
Israel will be able to sleep quietly for a while.
From a diplomatic point of view, the United States is unwavering in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers – not least thanks to the blockades that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of any Palestinian state.
Netanyahu’s Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these insidious Palestinians also slander and leave them a state of their own?
If they really had control over the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire missiles just like their counterparts in the Gaza Strip?
No, it is better to keep them behind the wall in check and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could make them a move through the bill.
Even if the Islamists, who are now in power in Egypt and other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense state is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to restore their economy.
That the pragmatic President Morsi teamed up with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
As the rest of the Arab world takes razor-sharp steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as this week a bus in Tel Aviv exploded.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push Hamas back into the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is the one that is represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, most of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states where Israel cedes territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence in enforcing this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms supplies to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by land swaps and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also move Hamas and Fatah to an agreement.
This would have done more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the upcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama also has to help move Israel to negotiations.
During his first term in office, he failed to conceive of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he is equally reluctant to participate.
But this is an unfortunate, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a vital interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian Laws on Uniform Cigarette Packaging Coming Into Force
Health warnings and sick body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging came into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and babies and children with cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, will be from next Saturday.
Australia introduces the world’s strictest regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
Studies have shown that people who haven’t started smoking at 26 are 99 percent more likely to stop smoking at 26 years of age.
"You can already see in young children that they understand the message of trying to promote tobacco companies with their brand image," says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek. She cites studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest rates of smoking in the world and the changes will only have a slight impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour black market trade, which would lead to cheaper and more easily accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
