In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored sometimes.
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to make myself a few thoughts of boredom.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is quite annoying - even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are leading boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us – and our children – to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to get lost in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us these days are almost constantly staring at one screen or another, we no longer benefit from the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome the boredom with open arms?
Oh, yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011), does not see this as such.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
The house walls of Pompeii decorate a Latin graffiti about boredom, dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of “wanting to do a satisfying job but not being able to do it”.
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In the case of apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in a “disruption of the attention process, coupled with bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly.”
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, even if we just have trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Ungaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - to German for example: "The inactive mind: The definition of boredom under the aspect of attention", which appeared in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to a paper on the previous volume, which was attended by a participant of the
Some groups listened to a loud TV show from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others listened to it at low volume, so it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television reported feeling more boredom than the two other groups - they had trouble concentrating, could find no reason for this, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you perform a monotonous activity - "as well as searching for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that squats and squats, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even combat them by keeping people physically more alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to crouch around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a buzzing loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
Some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a “boring vulnerability scale” in the 1980s.
On the scale, there are statements like "Many things I have to do are repeating themselves and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - particularly as regards the need for more and more variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a rather tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adults in school and homework were bored, while 23% said they were bored when they were not in school.
However, only 3% of parents reported feeling bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn’t know if the percentages of boredom have gone up or down.
However, he is sure that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have a great influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall for gambling or drugs to relieve them - this has been shown by studies.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors investigate the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you to do something else,” said Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
If you are bored and you use this energy to play guitar and cook, you will be happy.
However, television can create feelings of happiness in the short term, but in the long term these feelings become fleeting again.
So, if you give your bored child an iPad, it can relieve him of boredom, but he has not learned to entertain or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control is transferred from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to entertain himself, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we look at them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even away from the constant activity and technology training.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the agonizing, unceasing desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth, people are only looking for a way to disconnect and relax.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated, it’s hard to deal with once the noise is muted.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new Marihuana Act
19-year-old community college student and footballer Anthony Orozco is on trial in southeastern Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in this state: the possession of a few less marijuana blocks and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was charged with possession of drugs and drug utilities — cavalry offenses each punishable by a $100 fine — and received a court date.
