Regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - with a deadline until 1 December 2013.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is in any case ahead of most states when it comes to regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well-suited to orientation,” says Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Spirits Regulatory Authority.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve as a rough guide.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we can follow,” he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, comes into force on December 6 and thus also forms the end point of a gray area in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but ownership is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified at this time – such as how the state’s requirement of “reasonable access” to licensed marijuana should be agreed with the banning of cannabis businesses within 300 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent his employees in Aurora an e-mail stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses in individuals over 21 years of age, and that the police would "immediately" seek no criminal charges for those offenses.
Chief Oates added that the police will continue to enforce urban regulations to regulate growers of medical marijuana, and drug dealers will continue to be prosecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck represents a stricter view.
