As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are being acted as national model cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal selling, they are nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a criminal offence.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will resign.
Despite several startling arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former Obama administration drug policy adviser, is of the opinion that while criminal officials are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of the drugs, they will probably be stymied by tolerating legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not even waiting for the federal authorities to act.
