Our community has voted against this amendment.
We focus on what the community has chosen, not on what the state has chosen.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I am Tory
It’s not just college students today who are being attacked for their views.
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my elder brother had attended that university, which I once considered to be the world’s largest knowledge stamp, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization – free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of moving to Worscester College in the late 1980s — where I had planned to study history — I had packed my bags again, causing the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
In the Evening Standard it said I would have left because I had a problem with having classmates having sex in the neighboring room.
The author A N Wilson said insultingly that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth, however, was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had been harassed for only one reason – one reason that seemed so narrow and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: My now-deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to current reports, a new generation of moderate-rights students is suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and growing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for equal protection that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College’s Junior Common Room (JCR) state that they are “often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable” because of their political views.
They are calling for a place on their college’s Equal Opportunity Committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Their situation was aggravated by a recently aired documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed the Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of Oxford University’s Conservative Student Association, driving in a Rolls-Royce and bragging in a silver suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered "sin-bombs for introducing higher tuition fees."
20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of Nottingham University’s Conservative Student Association, said in a Sunday newspaper: “There is a growing leftist trend at universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without ever meeting us."
Samuel Roberts, 21 and history student in Corpus Christi, who initiated the quest for greater protection, is of the opinion that such a climate is "unpleasant." 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, appointed president of the Conservative Student Association of Oxford, says she has a growing dislike of JCR members.
“This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members,” she says.
In my first few weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to award an honorary degree to Margaret Thatcher - a former student - due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even frightened Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, where new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of the future events.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even participated with pleasure.
Political issues such as the mining workers’ strike, the privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against the apartheid regime in South Africa found their way into the wooden-paneled rooms of the tutorium.
At my first of these events, I had to translate French texts from the 18th century into English. I had not been caught on what was to come.
“Miss Wyatt,” said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), “please translate the first paragraph.”
I stumbled upon it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and pretty ugly.
“Are thatcher followers refusing to learn French, or are they just stupid?” he asked me.
The other students sneered.
There are tears in my eyes.
“I suggest they take a few French lessons in their spare time — so if you’re not too busy with your social activities,” Pitt grumbled to me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That night, I was sitting alone in college at dinner when someone tapped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it's the way it is.
Anyone suspected of being a Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub, I later tried to adjust.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove to be unsuccessful.
A beginner in philosophy, politics, and economics who had ironically attended Eton College, a conservative college, told me, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They beat each other, right?
I felt like homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and repress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay before me extended before my spiritual eye to a sweeping fire of esteem and isolation.
The only tutor who was openly identified as a Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for its Marxist-Determinist historical perspective.
In 1997 he took a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he told me.
I started commuting between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said softly.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming tower peaks.
Even my communist friends were always showing impeccable manners.
His moist eyes tingled.
Give the whole thing a chance.
I'm sure you're just being nailed.
It would break my heart if you went.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory follower, had given up on the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, in which another history teacher had seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Even though I secretly shrank from shame, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to “brainwashing” and called them “old fools.”
The relief only lasted a short time.
It was my father who hit the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my bunnies gave up.
As they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Feel free to call me a wintry flapping tail.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer such intimidation and malevolence in an educational institution.
And even more tragically, it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
