The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the Indonesian volcano’s bearers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur across the steep, stony paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by taking sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphurous gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur rocks that can weigh up to 70 kilograms in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb at the turtle's pace, keeping their balance and setting their steps carefully so that they do not slip out and crash.
They know that every step can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocent for every kilo of sulphur they mine.
Arriving at the top, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiresome heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which since 1960 exploits the deposits in the volcano and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for every kilo of sulfur.
This then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matchwoods, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who normally makes three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours, after which it is completely done, but at the end of the day it then has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable wage for such an almost inhuman effort, however, is three times what he would earn with fieldwork.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the bearer, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, and that for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as the sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are converted to Islam, and I have converted them to Hinduism, and I have converted them to Islam."
