Larry Hagman is dead.
Larry Hagman was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, and became world famous for his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series "Dallas", where he played a ruthless, deceitful and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the greed of the 80s, is dead.
He turned 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon of cancer complications, according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked the most," the family said.
Larry’s family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Harvest Thanksgiving celebrations.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died at Dallas Hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He made everyone who knew him happy.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original person and lived life to the fullest,” Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted that he had drunk a lot over the years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver, and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas" Hagman became known on television as a nice guy in the years 1965 to 1970 with the sitcom "Enchanting Jeannie" of the television station NBC.
There he played the astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is put on his head when he meets an attractive "jinn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live with him at home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, such as "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film works included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the enchantingly disgusting J.R. that made Hagman a superstar.
The CBS television series about the Ewing clan and other characters in their surroundings was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The ad slogan "Who shot J.R.?", which was supposed to create anticipation for an episode full of emotions where the character of Hagmann was almost killed, led to international speculation, and millions of dollars were wagered in betting houses.
The series reached a spectator record at the time.
When the answer was announced in a November 1990 chapter, it was seen by an average of 41 million viewers turning "Dallas" into the second most-watched entertainment program since the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
